Introduction

In this document, the relationship between the resale price of flats in Singapore and its independent variables are explored. The results are visualized and the resale price is predicted using the independent variables.

Source and selection of input data

The data was obtained from a Singapore Public Housing Dataset on Kaggle. Data obtained in August 2020 was chosen for building a model to price flat prices.

A short timeframe of one month with 2437 rows was chosen to ensure that computation remains fast during data exploration and visualization.

By convention, time series obtained during times of global economic instability is discouraged to be used for building models for prediction. There might be factors other than the ones given that affect the dependent variable to be predicted. Data from August 2020 was chosen as there were no news in that time period that might be followed by shocks in flat prices, as far as I know of.

These is the first 5 rows of the input table. A new column remaining_lease_months was created by converting remaining_lease from years and months into months. A new column storey was created by finding the average storey in storey_range. For example, if a flat is in the storey_range 01 TO 03, storey is 2.

These are the columns used for data exploration.

Data exploration

The most noticeable link between resale_price and the indepedent variables is its correlation with floor_area_sqm. There is a positive correlation between resale_price and floor_area_sqm as shown in Figure 1A.

To factor floor_area_sqm into resale_price, resale_price was divided by floor_area_sqm to obtain price_per_sqm. There is no correlation between price_per_sqm and floor_area_sqm as shown in Figure 1B.

The relationship between price_per_sqm and remaining_lease_months, distanceWithRaffles, distanceWithMrt and distanceWithMrt is shown in Figure 2. There is a slight negative correlation between price_per_sqm and distanceWithRaffles.

The median price_per_sqm is different between towns, as shown in Figure 3A. Flats in towns with higher connectivity and flats in towns that are close to important places tend to have higher prices. Bukit merah, Central Area, Marine Parade are within or on the edge of the CBD. Bishan has a high connectivity with the rest of the island with 3 MRT lines running through Bishan MRT Station and it is close to Orchard. Queenstown is close to Orchard by bus and it is close to NUS, NUH, Singapore Polytechnic, Biopolis and Fusionopolis. Towns such as Woodlands, Choa Chu Kang and Sembawang with lower connectivity and are further from the Central Area tend to have lower prices.

The price_per_sqm are centered to the median price_per_sqm by town, as shown in Figure 3A. The new measure of resale price is denoted with price_per_sqm_2 for brevity.

There is no correlation between price_per_sqm and remaining_lease_months, distanceWithRaffles, distanceWithMrt and distanceWithMrt is shown in Figure 4.

There is no difference in the median price_per_sqm_2 by flat_type, as shown in Figure 5.

There are differences in median price_per_sqm_2 and price_per_sqm_2 ranges between flat models (Figure 6A).

One possible reason for the difference in price_per_sqm_2 of flat models is the scarcity of the flat models. Flat models that are fewer in numbers in Singapore have higher prices. The frequency of the flat models in the input data was used as an indicator of the abundance of the flat models in Singapore. The boxplot in Figure 6A is reordered by descending frequency of flat models in Figure 6B. The hypothesis appears to be false.

The boxplot of lease_commence_date by flat_model is shown in Figure 6C. The flat models with 5 highest median price_per_sqm_2 have later lease commence dates, except for Terrace. Another possible reason for the difference in price_per_sqm_2 of flat models is the newness of the flat models.

Flats on higher storeys have higher median price_per_sqm_2 (Figure 7A). Flats on higher storeys (29 to 47) have generally higher prices.

One possible reason for the difference in price_per_sqm_2 of storeys is the scarcity of the storeys. Storeys that are fewer in numbers in Singapore have higher prices. The frequency of the storys in the input data was used as an indicator of the abundance of the storeys in Singapore. The boxplot in Figure 7A is reordered by descending frequency of storeys in Figure 6C. The hypothesis appears to hold.

The boxplot of lease_commence_date by storey is shown in Figure 7C. The storeys with 5 highest median price_per_sqm_2 have later lease commence dates.

Prediction of resale price

It is known that price_per_sqm_2 have no relationship with flat_type (Figure 5) and it has an inconclusive relationship with flat_model.

Despite knowing that price_per_sqm_2 have correlation with remaining_lease_months, distanceWithRaffles, distanceWithMrt and distanceWithGdPri (Figure 4), a linear model is tested if it could predict price_per_sqm_2 using remaining_lease_months, distanceWithRaffles, distanceWithMrt, distanceWithGdPri and storey.

The model is not a good model for predicting price_per_sqm_2. The Pearson correlation is 0.73 and the R2 is 0.53.

Conclusion

The dependent variable resale_price has a clear relationship with floor_area_sqm and town. It has no correlation with remaining_lease_months, distanceWithRaffles, distanceWithMrt, distanceWithGdPri. It has an inconclusive relationship with flat_model and storey.

Other than floor_area_sqm and town, the given factors cannot be used for predicting resale_price using a linear model. Future studies can include other factors and use other predictive models for predicting resale prices of flats in Singapore.
